a for the sacrifices they made for their families. Remembering the Samsui Women looks at who these women really are and at how both countries have commemorated their experiences. It is an illuminating study of the connection between memory and nation, including the politics of what is remembered and what is forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspectszChinazGuangdong Sheng. 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspectszSingapore. 0aSamsui womenzChinazGuangdong ShengxHistoryy20th century. 0aSamsui womenzChinazGuangdong ShengxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aSamsui womenzSingaporexHistoryy20th century. 0aSamsui womenzSingaporexSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomen immigrantszSingaporexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482577140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774825771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774825771/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles